arChildNodes.szComment: The accused barbarian kneels before Ealda, attempting to win her over with his new understanding of the cannibals--a twisted respect for them.
The accused barbrian stammers while continuing their defense of the cannibals, realizing they are treading on dangerous claims. They try to appeal to Ealda's pride as a barbarian. (a mistake)
Ealda interrupts the accused barbarian's defense, gravely offended by their claim that cannibals carry "honor."
The accused barbarian attempts to ignore Ealda's cold interruption, trying to turn his defense back towards "reason" and parallels of cannibals and barbarians.
Ealda interrupts the accused barbarian's defense. Ignoring his words, she coldly clarifies the true meaning of honor among barbarians--disgusted by his claims to cannibals sharing the same.
Desperate, the accused barbarian attempts a final defense--only to be quickly interrupted by Ealda.
Ealda cries out in fury, bellowing that the accused barbarian has no honor. (She follows this statement with a thunderous kick, sending the barbarian over the cliff to his death).
